-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Intercontinental Bank, National Bank Are Active
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-11-04T16:32:35Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-04/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-intercontinental-bank-national-bank-are-active.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  snapped two
days of declines, rising 0.2 percent to 83.76 at the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  added 0.2 percent to close at
1,865.75 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis. The  Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  climbed 0.2 percent to 24,822.03
by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, the first day of increases in
three. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  added 1.4 percent to
at 851.92 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek, while the  Ghana Stock Exchange
All-Share Index  advanced for a third day, climbing 0.1 percent
to 6,904.87 by 1 p.m. in Accra. A close at this level would the
strongest since Oct. 1.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Intercontinental Bank Plc  (INTERCON NL), a Nigerian lender
bailed out the country’s central bank last year, rose for an
eighth day, the longest streak of gains since January, adding 11
kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 2.38 naira. The company reported a
return to profit, with net income totaling 10.2 billion naira
($68 million) in the period through September compared with a
loss of 161.68 billion naira a year earlier, the company said in
a statement e-mailed by the Lagos-based Nigerian Stock Exchange
today. The bourse described the period as the third quarter
through September.  National Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (NBKL KN), a state-run lender,
rose to the highest in more than a week, adding 75 cents, or 1.9
percent, to 40.5 naira. Net income rose 39 percent to 1.35
billion shillings ($16.8 million) in the nine months through
September from a year earlier, the lender said in a statement
distributed by the Nairobi Stock Exchange yesterday.  To contact the reporters on this story:
